0.header:
A common cause of neck pain or stiff neck is a muscle strain or tension in the neck.

Stiff neck or neck pain discussed here assume you are having difficulty moving the neck, especially to one side.

Let's take a look at this neck pain.

1.header: Start by ruling out emergency situations that involve a stiff neck.

2.header: With this neck feeling stiff, do you also have fever or chills?

3.header:
Yes?
Let's rule out meningitis which is a medical emergency.

4.header: Are your eyes getting very sensitive to light?

5.header:
Yes?
Hmmm. This is a sign of meningitis. But don't panic yet.

Symptoms include:

  • Stiff neck
  • Fever and chills
  • Sensitivity to light

Let's answer a few more questions.

6.header: Do you have a severe headache in addition to this neck feeling stiff?

7.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Need to rule out meningitis.

8.header:
Are you getting confused with things around you?
And your neck is stiff?

10.header:
Try touching your chin to the chest.

Could you do this?

11.header:
Go to the Emergency Room.

Here is why:

  • If you cannot touch your chin to the chest with this stiff neck and you have more of the symptoms listed below, start heading to the emergency room.

Note:
We do not advice continuing for now. You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

Symptoms of meningitis include:

  • Stiff neck
  • Fever and chills
  • Sensitivity to light
  • Severe headache
  • Getting confused
  • Inability to touch the chin to the chest.

12.header:
We have tried to rule out meningitis.

Meningitis is a medical emergency.

If you are sure it does not apply to you, let's rule out something else before seeing what a pharmacist recommend for this neck pain.

Or do you want to go to a nearby hospital from the discussions so far?

20.header:
Are you experiencing numbness or tingling in your arms or hands?

Or feeling weak?

21.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • You might be looking at a nerve issue here.

22.header: Is the neck swollen or glands swollen with this stiff neck?

23.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Need to rule out infection.

24.header:
Do you have difficulty swallowing with this stiff neck?

Or difficulty breathing?

25.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Possible infection

26.header:
You just went through neck pain situations that may need urgent medical attention.

If your answer is "No" to the questions so far, you may be looking at a neck muscle sprain or strain.

You probably slept in a bad position or twisted the neck somehow.

Let's see what a pharmacist recommend over the counter to give you relief from this neck pain.

Would you like to do that or see the nearest urgent care clinic to you?

29.title: Chest congestion
dlg:
Sometimes when you have a cold or flu, the virus may spread to the nose, sinuses, throat and down to the tubes that take air to the lungs.

Inflammation of these tubes produces lots of mucus giving you a feeling of chest congestion just like in nasal or sinus congestion.

You will need to act fast to make sure this mucus does not trap bacteria which can lead to an infection like pneumonia.

Bronchitis is the swelling and inflammation of the tubes that take air to the lungs.

This may lead to narrowing of the airways and cause lots of mucus in the tubes producing shortness of breath, coughing and so on.

Usually, when the tubes start getting irritated, you will experience a dry, hacking cough,

With time the inflammation will produce mucus making the cough productive.

0.header:
Let's see what will take care of chest congestion over the counter.

We will talk about what you will describe as chest cold or having lots of mucus in the chest area.

1.header:
Was this chest congestion brought about after a cold, flu?

Or allergy symptoms?

2.header: Do you have a fever greater than 101°F with this chest congestion?

3.header:
Yes?
Let's rule out an infection of the lungs like pneumonia.

4.header: Are you coughing up greenish or thick yellowish mucus?

6.header:
What about mucus that is bloody or blood tinged or rust-colored?

Anything like that?

7.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Possible bacteria infection.

8.header: Are you experiencing shaking and or chills?

9.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Need to rule out pneumonia.

10.header:
Are you breathing faster than normal?

Faster heart beats?

12.header: What about shortness of breath when you try to climb the stairs or do some exercise?

13.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Need to rule out pneumonia.
  • The lungs are getting affected.

14.header:
Are you experiencing excessive sweating?

Or unusually sweating at night?

16.header: Try taking a deep breath or coughing out loud.

18.header:
Did you experience a stabbing or sharp chest pain?

Or did the chest pain you already have get worse?

19.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Sign and symptom of pneumonia infection.

20.header: Was this chest congestion getting better before and now it is getting bad again?

21.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • May have led to an infection.

22.header:
Those were the main signs and symptoms of pneumonia.

If they applied to you, seek urgent care.

Do not try to tough it out or do self care. It will only get worse and lead to complications.

If this is not the case, let's continue and see if you are looking at a simple case of bronchitis or something else.

30.header:
Did you experience a cough that started out dry and hacking?

And now it is bringing up mucus?

31.header: Let's make sure you are not looking at acute bronchitis.

32.header: Are you experiencing shortness of breath that get worse when you do something active?

33.header:
Yes?
This is a sign of acute bronchitis.

34.header:
You may have a low-grade fever.

Is this the case?

36.header:
Try Taking a deep breath.

Do you have a sensation of tightness or dull pain in the chest area?

37.header:
Yes?
This is a sign and symptom of acute bronchitis.

38.header: Is your energy level pretty low?

40.header: Has this been going on now for longer than 2 weeks?

41.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Risk of developing pneumonia increasing.

42.header:
Those were the signs and symptoms of acute bronchitis.

Just as you have a cold virus causing nasal congestion and sinus congestion. They can also cause congestion in the airways of the lungs.

The cold may be gone, but the congestion in the airways may remain.

If they are not cleared on time, they can trap bacteria leading to pneumonia, just as you would have a sinus infection.

If it is going on longer than 2 weeks, definitely seek urgent care or call the doctor for full evaluation.

Would you like to see the nearest urgent care clinic to you or see what is available over the counter for chest cold for now?

50.header:
No?
You will have to see a doctor on this one.

Self care is not adviced. You may have a serious problem.

First, let's rule out serious situations that can make it feel like you are having a chest cold.

51.header: Are you experiencing severe shortness of breath with this chest congestion feeling?

52.header:
Go to the Emergency Room.

Here is why:

  • Possible problem with the heart.
  • Possible anaphylactic reaction.

Note:
We do not advice continuing for now. You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

53.header:
Are you experiencing a swollen tongue?

Or swollen lips with a feeling of chest congestion?

54.header:
Go to the Emergency Room.

Here is why:

  • Possible anaphylactic reaction.

Note:
We do not advice continuing for now. You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

55.header:
What about chest feeling tight and painful?

With coughing?

56.header:
Go to the Emergency Room.

Here is why:

  • Possible heart attack.

Note:
We do not advice continuing for now. You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

57.header:
Do you have heart problems and it is like your chest is congested?

And you are working extra hard to breath?

58.header:
Go to the Emergency Room.

Here is why:

  • Congestive heart failure.

If you wake up from sleep after an hour or 2 due to shortness of breath, start heading to the emergency room.

Note:
We do not advice continuing for now. You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

59.header:
We tried to rule out emergency situations related to the chest feeling congested.

If your feeling of chest congestion is not due to a cold or flu, DO NOT try self care.

Seek urgent care or ER.

If you would like to take a look at out entry for a chest cold due to cold or flu symptoms, let's continue. Else start calling the doctor or heading to the emergency room.

30.title: Back Pain
dlg:
Know that it is itself a symptom of another medical condition, not a medical condition on its own.

Causes include slipped or herniated discs, injury, spinal stenosis, pregnancy, cancer to name a few.

Because of this, it is advisable to see a doctor as soon as possible to see what is causing it.

If sciatica is suspected by the doctor, he or she may test your strength, reflexes, and sensation.

0.header:
We will refer to pain felt in the lower back.

This is common because the lower back supports most of your body's weight.

Let's see what you are looking at.

1.header:
Did this back pain occur after a severe injury?

Severe blow or fall?

3.header: Is this back pain so bad you can hardly move?

4.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Over-the-counter pain reliever is not going to cut this.

5.header:
Let's have an idea of what may be causing this back pain.

This assumes no injury.

Know that back pain can be caused by many things. Even doctors have difficulties diagnosing back pain due to many factors involved.

Let's rule out anything major and see if over-the-counter remedies would give you relief until you see a specialist.

10.header:
Is this a pain that goes from the lower back into your buttocks and ...

... down the back of your thigh, calf and leg?

11.header:
Let's rule out sciatic nerve pain (sciatica) or herniated disc.

Know that sciatic nerve pain is a symptom of a herniated or slipped disc.

12.header:
Are you experiencing numbness and tingling of the affected leg?

Leg feeling weak?

13.header:
Yes?
This is a sign of sciatica.

You may have pain in one part of your leg and numbness in another.

14.header: Is this like a burning or stabbing pain?

16.header:
Try lifting your legs straight up while lying down.

Did the pain get worse?

17.header:
Yes?
Looking at a possible sciatic nerve pain.

18.header:
Try coughing, laughing or sneezing.

Did the pain get worse?

19.header:
Yes?
This is a sign of sciatic nerve pain (sciatica).

20.header:
Try bending the foot inward or downwards.

Are you having difficulty with this?

21.header:
Yes?
Pressure on the sciatic nerve can make this hard to do.

22.header:
Did this start suddenly?

And is getting severe?

23.header:
Yes?
Pressure on the sciatic nerve can make this hard to do.

You should seek a nearby urgent care clinic for this back pain. Or continue for now.

24.header:
Those were brief signs and symptoms of sciatica.

Sciatica occurs when there is pressure or injury to the sciatic nerve which starts in the lower spine and runs down the back of each leg.

If the pain is sharp and severe, you should seek urgent care or go to the emergency room.

If not, let's continue and see what a pharmacist suggests you do for now until you can see a doctor for a more comprehensive evaluation.

We will take a brief look at other possible causes of lower back pain before you see what you can use over the counter.

30.header:
Do you feel the pain anywhere else apart from the back?
(like in your hip, thigh, leg or feet)

31.header:
Yes?
Possible nerve pressure or damage in the spine area.

If the pain is sudden and sharp, you should seek urgent care or emergency room visit.

32.header: Do you have fever with this back pain?

33.header:
You should seek urgent professional care.

Here is why:

  • Possible infection
  • More serious than you think.

34.header: Is the back and spine red and/or swollen

35.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Need to rule out an infection

36.header: Do you also have blood in the urine with this back pain?

38.header: What about burning pain while urinating and your back is hurting you?

39.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Possible urinary tract infection
  • Kidney infection.

40.header: With this back pain is there also sudden loss of bowel or bladder control?

41.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Need to rule out severe nerve damage.

42.header: Does the affected area on the back feel tight like a knot?

43.header:
Yes?
Possible muscle spasm going on with the back muscles.

You will need to go to a nearby urgent care clinic. There are no muscle relaxants over-the-counter.

If the pain is not too severe, let's continue and see what a pharmacist suggest you do for now.

44.header:
Alright.
Assuming from here on that you are looking at a back muscle sprain / strain.

You will first feel back pain just after you:

  • Improperly lifted a heavy object
  • Suddenly exerted a physical effort
  • Slept on your stomach wrongly
  • Sat in one position for a long time
  • Sat with a thick wallet in your back pocket
  • Carried a heavy backpack or shoulder bag
  • Lack muscle tone
  • Have excess weight around your middle

Let's continue and see what a pharmacist recommend you do. Or do you think you should seek a nearby urgent care clinic from the discussions so far?

50.header: How bad is this back pain on a scale of 1 to 10

51.header:

Not too bad.

Let's see what a pharmacist recommend over the counter to help with this back pain.

Or would you like to see the nearest urgent care clinic to you?

31.title: Heartburn
dlg:
A little background

A band of muscle at the end of your esophagus called the lower esophageal sphincter (LES) closes off the esophagus after food and water leaves it and goes into the stomach.

If the LES does not close tightly enough, contents from the stomach such as food, liquid, and stomach acid can come back up (reflux) into the esophagus. This partly digested material can irritate the esophagus, causing heartburn and other symptoms.

0.header:
Heartburn is a burning sensation behind the breastbone.

The pain may rise in your chest and spread to your neck or throat.

If you have heartburn very often, you may have gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD).

Before we continue, let's rule out emergency situations.

1.header:
Symptoms of a heart attack can be mistaken for a heartburn.

Let's not assume anything and rule that out first.

2.header: Right now, does it feel like a tight band around the chest?

4.header: Does it feel like something heavy sitting on your chest?

5.header:
Yes?
Hmmm. Not looking good. Continue and see what you may be looking at.

6.header: What about squeezing or tightness of the chest area?

10.header:
Yes?
This is a symptom of a heart attack coming on.

Let's be sure you are not looking at a heart attack.

Be ready to call 911 if symptoms get worse. Be sure to consider the next questions carefully.

11.header: Do you have pain in one or both arms?

12.header:
Yes?
Chances you are looking at a heart attack increasing. Except if the pain is familiar to you.

13.header: Do you have pain in the neck or jaw?

14.header:
Yes?
Chances you are looking at a heart attack increasing. Except if the pain is familiar to you.

15.header: What about pain between the shoulder blades?

16.header:
Yes?
Chances you are looking at a heart attack increasing. Except if the pain is familiar to you.

17.header: Are you experiencing shortness of breath as we speak?

18.header:
Call 911 or seek emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Possible heart attack coming on.

Note:
We do not advice continuing. You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

19.header:
In addition to this chest pain or burning, are you sweating for no reason?

Did you break out in sweat?

20.header:
Call 911 or seek emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Possible heart attack coming on.

Note:
We do not advice continuing. You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

21.header: With this chest or burning pain are you feeling lightheaded and dizzy?

22.header:
Do you feel your heart is beating too fast?

Pounding?

23.header:
Call 911 or seek Emergency Room.

Here is why:

  • Need to rule out a heart attack going on.

Note:
We do not advice continuing. You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

24.header: What about feeling anxiety, like you are about to die?

25.header:
Call 911 or seek Emergency Room.

Here is why:

  • Possibility of a heart attack likely.

Note:
We do not advice continuing. You should only continue if you are not experiencing the question asked.

26.header:
Some symptoms of a heart attack can be mistaken for symptoms of a heartburn.

If you are feeling any of these symptoms in your chest area right now:

  • Like a tight band around the chest
  • Like something heavy sitting on the chest
  • Squeezing or tightness of the chest area

Consider this a medical emergency. These are warning signs of a heart attack.

If not and you have honestly answered the questions so far, then let's continue

30.header:
Some cases of heartburn require urgent care.

Others can be taken care of with over-the-counter medications.

Let's determine how bad it is and make the right decision.

31.header: Do you have blood in the stool or seen blood in your stool lately?

32.header:
Seek urgent care or call your doctor.

Here is why:

  • Possible stomach/intestinal bleeding

33.header:
Are you vomiting blood?

Or something like coffee grounds?

34.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • First priority is to stop the bleeding.
  • Then the cause will need to be figured out.
  • There are many reasons of vomiting blood.

35.header:
Are your stools black like tar?

Or maroon colored?

36.header:
Seek urgent care or emergency room.

Here is why:

  • Need to see the cause of the bleeding.

37.header:
Does it feel like food is stuck in the throat as it goes down?

Or you have difficulty swallowing?

38.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Your condition is worse than you can imagine.

39.header: Have you lost weight that you didn't want to lose lately?

40.header: Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

41.header:
Have you been using (over 2 weeks), any of the medications listed below?
  • Mylanta, Maalox (or store brands)
  • Pepcid, Tagamet, Zantac (or store brands)
  • Prilosec, Prevacid, Zegerid (or store brands)

42.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Need complete evaluation if no relief so far.

43.header:
Alright
We will assume a minor case of heartburn moving forward.

Let's take a look at the symptoms of a heartburn and be sure this is the case.

50.header:
Are you looking at a burning pain that starts in the chest or breastbone...

...and moves up toward the throat?

51.header:
Yes?
Heartburn can cause this.

Acid from the stomach flows backward (refluxes), irritating the delicate lining of the esophagus.

52.header: Any acidic or bitter taste in the mouth especially at the back of the throat?

53.header:
Yes?
This is a sign of heartburn.

More likely when you lay down.

The acid may move up towards the mouth especially if you did not use a pillow to prop your head up.

54.header: Any feeling that food is trying to come back into the throat?

55.header:
Yes?
This can be a symptom of a heartburn.

Symptoms include:

  • Burning pain in the chest or breastbone.
  • Burning pain that may move upward to the throat
  • Acidic or bitter taste in the back of the throat
  • Feeling that food is coming back into the throat

56.header: Does the pain come after you eat food?

58.header:
Does the severity of the pain increase when you lie down?

Or bend over?

59.header:
Yes?
This can be a sign and symptom of a heartburn.

Symptoms include:

  • Burning pain in the chest or breastbone.
  • Burning pain that may move upward to the throat
  • Acidic or bitter taste in the back of the throat
  • Feeling that food is coming back into the throat
  • Pain after meals
  • Increase severity of the pain when lying down or bending over.

60.header:
What about feeling bloated, belching?

Or a feeling of indigestion?

61.header:
Yes?
Too much acid in the stomach can cause this.

62.header: Any coughing especially at night?

63.header:
Yes?
This is a sign of heartburn.

This is due to the leaked (refluxed) acid irritating the windpipe.

64.header: Do you have a feeling of a lump in the throat?

65.header:
Yes?
This can be due to a heartburn.

Symptoms include:

  • Burning pain in the chest or breastbone.
  • Burning pain that may move upward to the throat
  • Acidic or bitter taste in the back of the throat
  • Feeling that food is coming back into the throat
  • Pain after meals
  • Increase severity of the pain when lying down or bending over.
  • Indigestion, belching
  • Night time cough
  • Lumpy feeling in the throat.

66.header:
Those were signs and symptoms of heartburn.

If you think you are looking at a heartburn, let's continue and figure out what triggers it.

Knowing this would go a long way towards providing relief.

If you can manage the triggers, then you would spend less money on over-the-counter medications. They can add up pretty quick.

70.header:
Let's use the criteria listed below to find answers that can help.

What is it, that is:

  • Increasing the amount of acid produced in the stomach?
  • Making the esophagus more sensitive to stomach acid?
  • Causing the valve called the lower esophageal sphincter (LES) to not function properly?
  • Increasing the pressure in the stomach leading to regurgitation?

Well, you've got the thinking process cut out for you. Let's get started.

72.header:
Are you a fan of most of the food types listed below?

Things like:

  • Chocolate
  • Citrus fruits and drinks
  • Tomatoes and tomatoes-based products
  • Spearmint, Peppermint
  • Raw onions, Garlic.

73.header:
Yes?
You would have to stay away from these.

These can make the stomach acid more irritating should it makes its way back to the esophagus.

74.header: Are you into fatty or oily greasy foods?

75.header:
Yes?
You will have to cut down on these as much as possible.

Here is why?

Both the greasy, fatty foods you ate and the acid your body produced to break them down will remain in the stomach for a longer time.

The acid will have a greater chance of moving back up (refluxing) into the esophagus.

76.header:
Still on food. Do you eat large meals at a time?

Or smaller meals more frequently?

77.header:
Large meals?
Cutting down to frequent smaller meals may help.

The stomach responds to large volume meals with large amounts of acid. More acid means a greater chance of acid reflux.

Remember, you have to reduce the chance of the stomach producing more acid than is needed.

78.header:
Do you normally finish eating your last meal of the day...

...at least 2 to 3 hours before going to bed?

79.header:
No?
Try eating the last meal of the day at least 2 to 3 hrs before bedtime.

This will give your food and the increased acid level a good chance to clear before you lay down.

This reduces the amount of acid that will likely reflux to cause heartburn.

Also, try sucking on a hard candy after you eat to stimulate more saliva that will help neutralize the acid that may have backed up when the esophagus valve opened.

80.header:
Are you currently taking any medications?

Not including medications for heartburn.

90.header: Let's take a look at medications and see which can cause heartburn.

91.header:
Are you taking any of the medications listed below?

Medications like:

  • Beta blockers (atenolol, propranolol)
  • Calcium-channel blockers (diltiazem, nifedipine).
  • Alpha blockers (prazosin)
  • Nitrates (isosorbide dinitrate, nitroglycerin)
  • Anticholinergics (e.g., for sea sickness).

92.header:
Yes?
These can increase the risk of developing heartburn.

They can relax the LES, lower esophageal sphincter, and increase reflux of stomach acid and juices into the esophagus. This can lead to heartburn.

93.header:
What about the medications listed below?

Talking about:

  • NSAIDS (ibuprofen, naproxen, aspirin, meloxicam)
  • COX-2 inhibitors (celebrex®)
  • Theophylline.

94.header:
Yes?
These can cause or worsen heartburn.

They irritate the stomach lining causing more acid to be produced and making the stomach more susceptible to the effect of the acid.

95.header:
Are you taking any of the ones listed below?

Medications like:

  • Benzodiazepines (diazepam, lorazepam, clonazepam, temazepam)
  • Tricyclic antidepressants (amitriptyline)

96.header:
Yes?
These can relax the LES, lower esophageal sphincter, causing acid reflux.

There is a strong link between heartburn during sleep and taking a benzodiazepine medication.

97.header: Do you take fosamax®, Boniva® or Actonel® ?

98.header:
Yes?
These can injure the lining of the esophagus.

You must drink a full glass of water with every dose and avoid lying down for 30 to 60 minutes afterward. Take this seriously.

99.header:
Narcotic pain relievers like morphine, meperidine, oxycodone. Are you taking those?

Or are you taking pain medications with hydrocodone?

100.header:
Yes?
These can worsen or cause heartburn or stomach upset at the very least.

Take these only when needed for pain.

101.header:
There are other medications that can cause heartburn.

If you just started taking a new medication and you are experiencing heartburn, check with the pharmacist and see if this is a side effect of the medication.

The goal is not to stop taking the medication but to know what you are dealing with.

Let's continue and check other things out.

110.header: Do you smoke cigarettes, cigars or pipes?

111.header:
Yes?
You will have to stop this. No way around it.

Smoking weakens the LES, lower esophageal sphincter, stimulate acid production and inhibit saliva production which is supposed to help protect the esophagus against the effect of stomach acid.

You will have to choose between smoking and serious heartburn pain. It is going to get progressively worse.

112.header: Do you chew gum often without food in the stomach?

113.header:
Yes?
You may have to put it off till after eating.

Chewing gum in an empty stomach may stimulate acid production in the stomach through a conditioned reflex action.

The stomach is used to expecting something when your mouth is moving or chewing. It produces acid and digestive juices in anticipation, but nothing shows up. You don't need this extra acid or digestive juices irritating your stomach.

In the same token, chewing gum for 30 minutes after eating a meal can help relieve heartburn.

114.header: Would you consider yourself overweight?

115.header:
Yes?
This can put extra pressure on the stomach causing acid reflux.

116.header: When exercising, do you do a lot of sit-ups?

117.header:
Yes?
May have to cut this down.

Sit-ups may increase the risk of acid reflux. Depends on how bad the heartburn is, you may have to do exercises that minimize pressure to the abdomen.

118.header:
Those were heartburn triggers to avoid.

Well, let's see what a pharmacist recommend for heartburn relief that is available over-the-counter.

Or would you like to see the nearest urgent care clinic to you if you think that is what you need?
